baseline_groups.claim_summary: YET program participation increases employment status (s_emp) among applicants, estimated via 2SLS with lottery as instrument.
baseline_groups.notes: Primary baseline. LATE of treatment on employment using lottery (offered) as instrument. Coef ~0.47, p=0.0.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: YET program participation increases educational enrollment (s_enrolled_edu) among applicants.
baseline_groups.notes: Secondary baseline. LATE of treatment on education enrollment. Coef ~0.084, p=0.004.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: YET program participation increases total income (s_tot_income) among applicants.
baseline_groups.notes: Secondary baseline. LATE of treatment on total income. Coef ~140.5, p=0.0.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: YET program participation increases the probability of working and studying simultaneously (s_wstudy).
baseline_groups.notes: Secondary baseline. LATE of treatment on working-while-studying. Coef ~0.435, p=0.0.

baseline_groups.claim_summary: YET program participation decreases the probability of neither working nor studying (s_nwnstudy).
baseline_groups.notes: Secondary baseline. LATE of treatment on NEET status. Coef ~-0.121, p<0.001.

global_notes: The paper has one primary claim (employment effect, G1) and four secondary outcome claims (G2-G5). The specification search covers robustness checks (control variations, sample restrictions, estimation methods) plus alternative outcomes (soft skills, education metrics, industry composition), heterogeneity analyses, and placebo/balance tests. Many leave-one-out control specs produce identical coefficients to the baseline, suggesting the dropped variables were not in the baseline control set. The first-stage and reduced-form specs are diagnostics, not core tests.
